We need to “build up” the income‐statement’s “expenses” item from the transaction data. In our table the “expense” entries appear as rows whose “type” begins with “Expense” (for example Administrative Expenses or Sales Expenses) as well as rows reporting “Depreciation” (which is included in expenses). (Transactions such as “Purchase”, “Initial…” and “Sale” are not expense items; and although some rows concern “Interest Receivables” they do not fall into expenses for the income statement.) 

Thus, we scan the table and add up each amount on rows having a type beginning with “Expense” or “Depreciation.” (We now describe the process in brief, showing the key rows and then summing them.)
